\begin{tikzpicture} [scale=1.2]
\coordinate (C) at (0,0);
\coordinate (A) at (2.2,0);
\coordinate (B) at (103.1:1);

\draw[black] (A) node[anchor= west] {$A$};
\draw[black] (B) node[anchor=south, xshift=-2] {$B$};
\draw[black] (C) node[anchor=north, xshift=-2] {$C$};

\draw[black, thick] (C)--(B) node[left,midway, yshift=-2, text=blue] {$a=5$};
\draw[black, thick] (A)--(B) node[above,midway, text=blue] {$c$};
\draw[black, thick] (A)--(C) node[below,midway, text=blue] {$b=11$};
\draw[red, thick] (103.1:.7) arc(-76.9:-21.9:.3) node[below right,midway,xshift=-2] {$55\degree$};
\end{tikzpicture}

solution.p:
We must find the three remaining parts of the triangle, A, C, and c. First, we use the Law of Sines to find \sin (A).
        \dfrac{\sin (A)}{a} \amp = \dfrac{\sin (B)}{b} \amp\amp \blert{\text{Substitute the known values.}}
            \dfrac{\sin (A)}{5} \amp = \dfrac{\sin (55\degree)}{11} \amp\amp \blert{\text{Multiply both sides by 5.}}
            \sin (A) \amp = 5 \cdot \dfrac{\sin (55\degree)}{11} \approx 0.3723
So A = \sin^{-1}(0.3723) \approx 21.9\degree. Now we know two angles, and we can find angle C.
        C \amp = 180\degree - (B + A)
            \amp = 180\degree - 55\degree - 21.9\degree = 103.1\degree
Finally, we use the Law of Sines to find side c.  
        \dfrac{c}{\sin (C)} \amp = \dfrac{b}{\sin (B)} \amp\amp \blert{\text{Substitute the known values.}}
            \dfrac{c}{\sin (103.1\degree)} \amp = \dfrac{11}{\sin (55\degree)} \amp\amp 
                \begin{array}{l}
                    \blert{\text{Multiply both sides by }}\\
                    \blert{\sin (103.1\degree).}
                 \end{array}
            c \amp = \dfrac{11}{\sin (55\degree)} \cdot \sin (103.1\degree)
Evaluating this expression with a calculator gives c \approx 13.1.

